husband was diagnosed in childhood with a metabolic condition caused by a mitochondrial DNA point mutation. Several members of his extended family are also affected by the same disorder.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most accurate estimate of the probability that this couple\u0027s baby will inherit the same metabolic disorder as the father?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["100%","75%","50%","25%","0%"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that there is a \u003Cstrong\u003E0%\u003C/strong\u003E probability of the baby inheriting the same metabolic disorder as the father. This is because this disorder is caused by a mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) point mutation, and mtDNA is inherited exclusively from the mother.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMitochondria are organelles found in the cytoplasm of cells, and they contain their own DNA (mtDNA) separate from the nuclear DNA. During fertilisation, the sperm contributes only nuclear DNA to the zygote, while the egg cell contributes both nuclear and mitochondrial DNA. As a result, all mitochondria (and thus all mtDNA) in a developing embryo come from the mother\u0027s egg cell.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options (\u003Cstrong\u003E25%\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003E50%\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003E75%\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003E100%\u003C/strong\u003E) are incorrect because they imply some possibility of paternal transmission of mitochondrial DNA, which does not occur in humans. These percentages are more commonly associated with autosomal dominant (50%), autosomal recessive (25% if one parent is a carrier, 100% if both parents are affected), or X-linked inheritance patterns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERANZCOG recommend couples planning pregnancy to undergo Reproductive Carrier Screening for recessive (AR and XLR) conditions and that there is now a medicare funded 3-gene screen for couples that looks for CF, SMA and FRAX variants.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mitochondrial DNA is inherited exclusively from the mother, so a father cannot pass mitochondrial DNA mutations to his children."],"references":["Roberts, I. Nelson\u2019s textbook of pediatrics (20th edn.), by R. Kliegman, B. Stanton, J. St. Geme, N. Schor (eds). Pediatr Radiol 47, 1364\u20131365 (2017). https://doi.org/10.1007/s00247-017-3907-9"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33783"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13948"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33783"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-17T09:07:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-04T07:56:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6578"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48811"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updat